Usage: Usage: ocamlopt <options> <files>
Options are: <options> <files>
Try 'Usage: ocamlopt <options> <files>
Options are: --help' for more information.
  -fno-asan  Disable AddressSanitizer. This is only meaningful if the compiler was built with AddressSanitizer support enabled.
  -fcssc  Enable the Common Short Sequence Compression (CSSC) instructions.
  -gupstream-dwarf  Only emit the same DWARF information as the upstream compiler
  -gno-upstream-dwarf  Emit potentially more DWARF information than the upstream compiler. Implies -shape-format debugging-shapes.
  -gdwarf-inlined-frames  Emit DWARF inlined frame information
  -gno-dwarf-inlined-frames  Do not emit DWARF inlined frame information
  -gstartup  Emit potentially more DWARF information
     for the startup file than the upstream compiler
     (only takes effect with -gno-upstream-dwarf)
  -gno-startup  Emit the same DWARF information for the
     startup file as the upstream compiler
  -gdwarf-may-alter-codegen  Allow code generation (and
     when finalizers may run, etc) to be altered
     in order to produce a better debugging experience
  -gno-dwarf-may-alter-codegen  Do not alter code generation when emitting debugging information
  -gdwarf-may-alter-codegen-experimental  Like -gdwarf-may-alter-codegen but with more experimental features.
     Implies -gdwarf-may-alter-codegen.
     THIS MAY GENERATE BROKEN CODE.
  -gno-dwarf-may-alter-codegen-experimental  Disable experimental changes to code generation when emitting
     debugging information.
  -gdwarf-max-function-complexity  Maximum function
     complexity above which -gno-upstream-dwarf information
     will not be emitted, to improve compilation time (default 50)
  -gdwarf-compression  Set the DWARF compression format (default zlib)
  -gdwarf-fission  Set the DWARF fission method: none, objcopy, or dsymutil.
     Default: none (dsymutil on macOS with --enable-oxcaml-dwarf).
     Only takes effect with -gno-upstream-dwarf or --enable-oxcaml-dwarf
  -gdwarf-pedantic  Enable pedantic DWARF error checking (fatal errors instead of silent fallbacks)
  -dump-inlining-paths  Dump inlining paths when dumping flambda2 terms
  -davail  Dump register availability information
  -dranges  Dump results of Compute_ranges
  -ddebug-invariants  Run invariant checks during generation of debugging information
  -ddebug-available-regs  Enable debug output for available registers analysis
  -ddwarf-types  Enable debug output for DWARF type generation
  -ddwarf-metrics  Write DWARF metrics to auxiliary JSON file .debug-stats.json, which can then be aggregated with the analyze_debug_stats.py Python script.
  -ddwarf-metrics-output-file <file>  Set output filename for DWARF metrics data
  -ocamlcfg  Use ocamlcfg (deprecated, does nothing)
  -no-ocamlcfg  Do not use ocamlcfg (deprecated, does nothing)
  -dcfg  (undocumented)
  -dcfg-invariants  Extra sanity checks on Cfg
  -regalloc {cfg|irc|ls|gi} Select the register allocator
  -regalloc-linscan-threshold  Use linscan on functions with more temporaries than the threshold (default is 100000)
  -regalloc-param  Pass a parameter to the register allocator
  -regalloc-validate  Validate register allocation
  -no-regalloc-validate  Do not validate register allocation
  -vectorize  Enable vectorizer (EXPERIMENTAL)
  -no-vectorize  Disable vectorizer (EXPERIMENTAL)
  -vectorize-max-block-size <n>  Only CFG block with at most n IR instructions will be vectorized (default 100)
  -dvectorize  (undocumented)
  -cfg-peephole-optimize  Apply peephole optimizations to CFG
  -no-cfg-peephole-optimize  Do not apply peephole optimizations to CFG
  -x86-peephole-optimize  Apply peephole optimizations to x86
  -no-x86-peephole-optimize  Do not apply peephole optimizations to x86
  -no-x86-peephole-remove-mov-to-dead-register  Disable x86 peephole: remove mov to dead register
  -no-x86-peephole-remove-redundant-cmp  Disable x86 peephole: remove redundant cmp
  -no-x86-peephole-combine-add-rsp  Disable x86 peephole: combine adjacent add rsp
  -cfg-stack-checks  Insert the stack checks on the CFG representation
  -no-cfg-stack-checks  Insert the stack checks on the linear representation
  -cfg-stack-checks-threshold <n>  Only CFGs with fewer than n blocks will be optimized
  -cfg-eliminate-dead-trap-handlers  Eliminate dead trap handlers
  -no-cfg-eliminate-dead-trap-handlers  Do not eliminate dead trap handlers
  -cfg-prologue-validate  Validate prologues added to CFG
  -no-cfg-prologue-validate  Do not validate prologues added to CFG
  -cfg-prologue-shrink-wrap  Place prologues optimally in the CFG to minimise unnecessary prologue executions
  -no-cfg-prologue-shrink-wrap  Place prologues at the entrypoint of the CFG
  -cfg-prologue-shrink-wrap-threshold <n>  Only CFGs with fewer than n blocks will be shrink-wrapped
  -cfg-merge-blocks  Merge equivalent CFG blocks
  -no-cfg-merge-blocks  Do not merge equivalent CFG blocks
  -cfg-value-propagation  Propagate value to simplify CFG
  -no-cfg-value-propagation  Do not propagate value to simplify CFG
  -cfg-value-propagation-float  Propagate float value to simplify CFG
  -no-cfg-value-propagation-float  Do not propagate float value to simplify CFG
  -cfg-value-propagation-flow  Propagate values across block to simplify CFG
  -no-cfg-value-propagation-flow  Do not propagate values across block to simplify CFG
  -reorder-blocks-random <seed> Randomly reorder basic blocks in every function, using the provided seed (intended for testing, off by default).
  -basic-block-sections  (option not available)
  -module-entry-functions-section  (option not available)
  -dasm-comments  Add comments in .s files (e.g. for DWARF)
  -dno-asm-comments  Do not add comments in .s files
  -heap-reduction-threshold  Threshold (in major words, defaulting to 62500000) to trigger a heap reduction before code emission
  -zero-alloc-check {default|all|opt|none} Check that annotated functions do not allocate and do not have indirect calls. 
    The argument specifies which annotations to check: 
      "opt" means attributes with "opt" payload and is intended for debugging;
      "default" means attributes without "opt" payload; 
      "all" covers both "opt" and "default" and is intended for optimized builds.
  -zero-alloc-assert {default|all|all_opt} Add zero_alloc annotations to all functions.
    The argument specifies which annotations to use: 
      "all" is equivalent to adding [@@@zero_alloc all]
      "all_opt" is equivalent to adding [@@@zero_alloc all_opt]
      "default" does not add any attributes.
  -dzero-alloc  (undocumented)
  -disable-zero-alloc-checker  Conservatively assume that all functions may allocate, without checking. Disables computation of zero_alloc function summaries, unlike "-zero-alloc-check none" which disables checking of zero_alloc annotations)
  -disable-precise-zero-alloc-checker  Conservatively assume that all forward calls and mutually recursive functions may allocate. Disables fixed point computation of summaries for these functions. Intended as a temporary workaround when precise analysis is too expensive.
  -zero-alloc-checker-details-cutoff  Do not show more than this number of error locations in each function that fails the check (default 20, negative to show all)
  -zero-alloc-checker-details-extra  Show extra details in error messages from zero_alloc checker
  -no-zero-alloc-checker-details-extra  Do not show extra details in error messages from zero_alloc checker
  -zero-alloc-checker-join  How many abstract paths before losing precision (default 100, negative to fail instead of widening, 0 to keep all)
  -function-layout {topological|source} Order of functions in the generated assembly (default: source)
  -name-mangling-scheme {flat|structured} Override the default name mangling scheme set at configure time
  -disable-builtin-check  If an external annotated with [@@builtin] is not recognized, fall back to the corresponding C stub, instead of compilation error.
  -disable-poll-insertion  Do not insert poll points
  -enable-poll-insertion  Insert poll points
  -symbol-visibility-protected  Emit global symbols with visibility STV_PROTECTED on supported systems
  -no-symbol-visibility-protected  Emit global symbols with visibility STV_DEFAULT
  -long-frames  Allow stack frames longer than 2^16 bytes
  -no-long-frames  Do not allow stack frames longer than 2^16 bytes
  -debug-long-frames-threshold n debug only: set long frames threshold
  -caml-apply-inline-fast-path  Inline the fast path of caml_applyN
  -internal-assembler Write object files directly instead of using the system assembler (x86-64 ELF only)
  -verify-binary-emitter  Verify binary emitter output matches system assembler output. Exits with error on mismatch. (ARM64 only)
  -dissector  Enable the dissector pass (prevents relocation overflow when linking very large executables with the small code model).  (Experimental)
  -dissector-partition-size <size>  Set the partition size threshold in gigabytes for the dissector pass (default: 1)
  -ddissector  Print verbose logging from the dissector pass
  -ddissector-sizes  Dump allocated section sizes for each input file during linking
  -ddissector-verbose  Print detailed per-relocation logging from the dissector pass
  -ddissector-partitions  Keep partition .o files and print their paths (for debugging)
  -ddissector-inputs <file>  Write dissector input analysis to <file>
  -dissector-assume-lld-without-64-bit-eh-frames  Assume LLD linker without 64-bit EH frame support (default)
  -no-dissector-assume-lld-without-64-bit-eh-frames  Do not assume LLD linker limitation
  -manual-module-init  Enable manual module initialization (emit unit dependency table)
  -no-manual-module-init  Disable manual module initialization (default)
  -dgc-timings Output information about time spent in the GC
  -no-mach-ir  Avoid using the Mach IR (kept temporarily only for backward compatibility, has no effects)
  -dllvmir  (undocumented)
  -keep-llvmir  Keep the LLVM IR file produced by -llvm-backend
  -llvm-path  Specify which LLVM compiler to use
  -llvm-flags  Extra flags to pass to LLVM (like -march or -mtune)
  -flambda2-debug  Enable debug output for the Flambda2 pass
  -no-flambda2-debug  Disable debug output for the Flambda2 pass
  -reaper-debug-flags  Debug flags for the reaper pass
  -flambda2-join-points  Propagate information from all incoming edges to a join
     point (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-join-points  Propagate information to a join point only if there are
     zero or one incoming edge(s) (default) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-result-types-functors-only  Infer result types for functors (but no other
     functions) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-result-types-all-functions  Infer result types for all functions
     (including functors) (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-result-types  Do not infer result types for functions (or
     functors) (default) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-basic-meet  Use a basic meet algorithm (deprecated, does nothing) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-advanced-meet  Use an advanced meet algorithm (deprecated, does nothing) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-join-algorithm {binary|n-way|checked} Select the join algorithm to use (Flambda 2 only)
      Valid values are: 
       "binary" is the legacy binary join;
       "n-way" is the new n-way join;
       "checked" runs both algorithms and compares them (use for debugging).
  -flambda2-unbox-along-intra-function-control-flow  Pass values within
     a function as unboxed where possible (default) (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-unbox-along-intra-function-control-flow  Pass values within
     a function in their normal representation (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-backend-cse-at-toplevel  Apply the backend CSE pass to module
     initializers (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-backend-cse-at-toplevel  Do not apply the backend CSE pass to
     module initializers (default) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-cse-depth  Depth threshold for eager tracking of CSE equations
     (default 2) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-join-depth  Depth threshold for alias expansion in join
     (default 5) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-reaper  Enable reaper pass (Flambda2 only)
  -no-flambda2-reaper  Disable reaper pass (default) (Flambda2 only)
  -reaper-preserve-direct-calls {never|always|zero-alloc|auto} Choose the direct call preservation strategy of the reaper (Flambda2 only)
      Valid values are: 
       "never": do not try to preserve direct calls to old functions;
       "always": always preserve existing direct calls;
       "zero-alloc": preserve direct calls only in zero-alloc checked;
       "auto": preserve direct calls only when the reaper is unable to identify a set of possibly called functions.
  -reaper-local-fields  Enable local field handing in the reaper (Flambda2 only)
  -no-reaper-local-fields  Disable local field handing in the reaper (default) (Flambda2 only)
  -reaper-unbox  Enable unboxing in the reaper (default) (Flambda2 only, requires -reaper-change-calling-conventions)
  -no-reaper-unbox  Disable unboxing in the reaper (Flambda2 only)
  -reaper-max-unbox-size  Maximum number of fields unboxed by the reaper for a single block (default 10) (Flambda2 only)
  -reaper-change-calling-conventions  Allow the reaper to change the calling conventions of functions (default) (Flambda2 only)
  -no-reaper-change-calling-conventions  Prevent the reaper from changing the calling conventions of functions (Flambda2 only)
  -flambda2-expert-fallback-inlining-heuristic  Prevent inlining of functions
     whose bodies contain closures (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-expert-fallback-inlining-heuristic  Allow inlining of functions
     whose bodies contain closures (default) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-expert-inline-effects-in-cmm  Allow inlining of effectful
     expressions in the produced Cmm code
     into any context (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-expert-inline-effects-in-cmm  Only allow inlining of effectful
     expressions in the produced Cmm code into
     the arguments of allocation primitives (default) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-expert-cmm-safe-subst  Prevent potentially unsafe substitutions in cmm but may produce less optimized code
  -no-flambda2-expert-cmm-safe-subst  Allow more substitutions in cmm, even ones that may be unsafe (default)
  -flambda2-expert-phantom-lets  Generate phantom lets when -g
     is specified (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-expert-phantom-lets  Do not generate phantom lets even when -g
     is specified (default) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-expert-max-block-size-for-projections  Do not simplify projections
     from blocks if the block size exceeds this value (default not set)
     (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-expert-max-unboxing-depth  Do not unbox (nested) values deeper
     than this many levels (default 3) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-expert-can-inline-recursive-functions  Consider inlining
      recursive functions (default ) (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-expert-can-inline-recursive-functions  Only inline recursive
     functions if forced to so do by an attribute
     (default  (default)) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-expert-max-function-simplify-run  Do not run simplification of function more
     than this (default 2) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-expert-shorten-symbol-names  Shorten symbol names (Flambda 2 only, set by
     default in classic mode)
  -no-flambda2-expert-shorten-symbol-names  Do not shorten symbol names (Flambda 2 only, set by
     default except for classic mode)
  -flambda2-expert-cont-lifting-budget  Set the limit of extra parameters introduced
 when lifting continuations (per function)
  -flambda2-expert-cont-specialization-budget  Set the limit on the number of continuations 
 copied/generated when specializing a continuation (per function)
  -flambda2-debug-concrete-types-only-on-canonicals  Check that concrete
     types are only assigned to canonical
     names (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-debug-concrete-types-only-on-canonicals  Do not check that
     concrete types are only assigned to canonical
     names (default) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-debug-keep-invalid-handlers  Keep branches simplified
     to Invalid (default) (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-debug-keep-invalid-handlers  Delete branches simplified
     to Invalid (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-max-depth <int>|<round>=<int>[,...]
     Maximum depth of search for inlining opportunities inside
     inlined functions (default 1) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-max-rec-depth <int>|<round>=<int>[,...]
     Maximum depth of search for inlining opportunities inside
     inlined recursive functions (default 0) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-alloc-cost <float>|<round>=<float>[,...]
     The cost of not removing an allocation during inlining
     (default 0.875, higher = more costly) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-branch-cost <float>|<round>=<float>[,...]
     The cost of not removing a conditional during inlining
     (default 0.625, higher = more costly) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-call-cost <float>|<round>=<float>[,...]
     The cost of not removing a call during inlining
     (default 0.625, higher = more costly) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-prim-cost <float>|<round>=<float>[,...]
     The cost of not removing a primitive during inlining
     (default 0.375, higher = more costly) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-indirect-cost <float>|<round>=<float>[,...]
     The cost of not removing an indirect call during inlining
     (default 0.500, higher = more costly) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-poly-compare-cost <float>|<round>=<float>[,...]
     The cost of not removing a polymorphic comparison during inlining
     (default 1.250, higher = more costly) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-small-function-size <int>|<round>=<int>[,...]
     Functions with a cost less than this will always be inlined
     unless an attribute instructs otherwise (default 10)
     (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-large-function-size <int>|<round>=<int>[,...]
     Functions with a cost greater than this will never be inlined
     unless an attribute instructs otherwise (default 10); speculative
     inlining will be disabled if equal to the small function size
     (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-small-functor-size <int>|<round>=<int>[,...]
     Functors with a cost less than this will always be inlined
     unless an attribute instructs otherwise (default 10)
     (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-large-functor-size <int>|<round>=<int>[,...]
     Functors with a cost greater than this will never be inlined
     unless an attribute instructs otherwise (default 2000000); speculative
     inlining will be disabled if equal to the small functor size
     (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inline-threshold <float>|<round>=<float>[,...]
     Aggressiveness of inlining (default 10.00, higher numbers mean
     more aggressive) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-speculative-inlining-only-if-arguments-useful  Only
    perform speculative inlining if the Flambda type system has
    useful information about the argument(s) at the call site (default)
    (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-speculative-inlining-only-if-arguments-useful  Ignore
     whether the Flambda type system has useful information
     about the argument(s) at the call site when performing
     speculative inlining (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-speculative-inlining-track-lifted-constants  Track the size of lifted constants when doing speculative inlining
    (Flambda 2 only)
  -no-flambda2-speculative-inlining-track-lifted-constants  Do not track the size of lifted constants when doing speculative
    inlining (default) (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-inlining-report-bin  Write inlining report
     in binary format (Flambda 2 only)
  -flambda2-unicode  Use Unicode output when printing
     Flambda 2 code
  -flambda2-kind-checks  Perform kind checks on Flambda 2
     code (may cause fatal errors with layout-poly GADT code)
  -drawfexpr  Like -drawflambda but outputs fexpr language
     (Flambda 2 only)
  -drawfexpr-to <file> Like -drawfexpr but dumps to given file (Flambda 2 only)
  -dfexpr  Like -dflambda but outputs fexpr language
     (Flambda 2 only)
  -dfexpr-to <file> Like -dfexpr but dumps to given file (Flambda 2 only)
  -dfexpr-after {simplify|reaper} <pass> Like -dfexpr, but dumps after the provided pass (Flambda 2 only)
  -dfexpr-annot  Dump fexpr of all passes alongside each compilation unit
     (Flambda 2 only)
  -dfexpr-annot-after  Dump fexpr of given pass alongside each compilation unit
     (Flambda 2 only)
  -dslot-offsets  Dump closure offsets (Flambda 2 only)
  -dfreshen  Freshen bound names when printing (Flambda 2 only)
  -dflow  Dump debug info for the flow computation (Flambda 2 only)
  -dsimplify  Print Flambda 2 terms after simplify (Flambda 2 only)
  -dreaper  Dump debug info for the reaper pass (Flambda 2 only)
  -use-cached-generic-functions  Use the cached generated functions
  -cached-generic-functions-path <file>  Set the path of the cached generic functions (default to cached-generic-functions.o)
  -a  Build a library
  -alert <list>  Enable or disable alerts according to <list>:
        +<alertname>  enable alert <alertname>
        -<alertname>  disable alert <alertname>
        ++<alertname> treat <alertname> as fatal error
        --<alertname> treat <alertname> as non-fatal
        @<alertname>  enable <alertname> and treat it as fatal error
    <alertname> can be 'all' to refer to all alert names
  -absname  Show absolute filenames in error messages
  -no-absname  Do not try to show absolute filenames in error messages (default)
  -locs  Print line and column numbers in error messages (default)
  -no-locs  Do not print line and column numbers in error messages
  -afl-instrument Enable instrumentation for afl-fuzz
  -afl-inst-ratio Configure percentage of branches instrumented
     (advanced, see afl-fuzz docs for AFL_INST_RATIO)
  -annot  (deprecated) Save information in <filename>.annot
  -as-argument-for <module name> Compile the module as an argument for the named parameter.
  -as-parameter  Compile the interface as a parameter module.
  -bin-annot  Save typedtree in <filename>.cmt
  -bin-annot-cms  Save shapes in <filename>.cms
  -bin-annot-occurrences  Store every occurrence of a bound name in the .cmt file.
This information can be used by external tools to provide
features such as project-wide occurrences. This flag has
no effect in the absence of '-bin-annot'.
  -inline-branch-factor <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  Estimate the probability of a branch being cold as 1/(1+n) (used for inlining) (default 0.10)
  -c  Compile only (do not link)
  -cc <command>  Use <command> as the C compiler and linker
  -cclib <opt>  Pass option <opt> to the C linker
  -ccopt <opt>  Pass option <opt> to the C compiler and linker
  -cmi-file <file>  Use the <file> interface file to type-check
  -clambda-checks  Instrument clambda code with closure and field access checks (for debugging the compiler)
  -Oclassic  Make inlining decisions at function definition time rather than at the call site (replicates previous behaviour of the compiler).  Implies -linscan (and causes -nolinscan to be ignored).
  -color {auto|always|never}  Enable or disable colors in compiler messages
    The following settings are supported:
      auto    use heuristics to enable colors only if supported
      always  enable colors
      never   disable colors
    The default setting is 'auto', and the current heuristic
    checks that the TERM environment variable exists and is
    not empty or "dumb", and that isatty(stderr) holds.
  If the option is not specified, these setting can alternatively
  be set through the OCAML_COLOR environment variable.
  -error-style {contextual|short}  Control the way error messages and warnings are printed
    The following settings are supported:
      short       only print the error and its location
      contextual  like "short", but also display the source code
                  snippet corresponding to the location of the error
    The default setting is 'contextual'.
  If the option is not specified, these setting can alternatively
  be set through the OCAML_ERROR_STYLE environment variable.
  -compact  Optimize code size rather than speed
  -config  Print configuration values and exit
  -config-var  Print the value of a configuration variable, without a newline, and exit
    (print nothing and exit with error value if the variable does not exist)
  -dtypes  (deprecated) same as -annot
  -disable-all-extensions   Legacy, use [-extension-universe no_extensions].
    Disable all extensions, wherever they have been specified; this
    flag overrides prior uses of the -extension flag, disables any
    extensions that are enabled by default, and causes future uses of
    the -extension flag to raise an error.
  -ikinds  Enable ikinds-based kind checker (experimental)
  -ikinds-debug  Enable ikinds debug logging
  -only-erasable-extensions  Legacy, use [-extension-universe upstream_compatible].
    Disable all extensions that cannot be "erased" to attributes,
    wherever they have been specified; this flag overrides prior
    contradictory uses of the -extension flag, raises an error on
    future such uses, and disables any such extensions that are
    enabled by default.
    (Erasable extensions: mode, mode_beta, mode_alpha, unique, unique_beta, unique_alpha, overwriting, layouts, layouts_beta, layouts_alpha, layout_poly, layout_poly_beta, layout_poly_alpha)
  -extension {comprehensions|mode|mode_beta|mode_alpha|unique|unique_beta|unique_alpha|overwriting|include_functor|polymorphic_parameters|immutable_arrays|module_strengthening|layouts|layouts_beta|layouts_alpha|simd|simd_beta|simd_alpha|small_numbers|small_numbers_beta|small_numbers_alpha|instances|let_mutable|layout_poly|layout_poly_beta|layout_poly_alpha|runtime_metaprogramming}  Enable the specified extension (may be specified more than once)
  -no-extension {comprehensions|mode|mode_beta|mode_alpha|unique|unique_beta|unique_alpha|overwriting|include_functor|polymorphic_parameters|immutable_arrays|module_strengthening|layouts|layouts_beta|layouts_alpha|simd|simd_beta|simd_alpha|small_numbers|small_numbers_beta|small_numbers_alpha|instances|let_mutable|layout_poly|layout_poly_beta|layout_poly_alpha|runtime_metaprogramming}  Disable the specified extension (may be specified more than once)
  -extension-universe {no_extensions|upstream_compatible|stable|beta|alpha} Set the extension universe and enable all extensions in it. Each universe
    allows a set of extensions, and every successive universe includes 
    the previous one.
  -for-pack <ident>  Generate code that can later be `packed' with
     ocamlopt -pack -o <ident>.cmx
  -g  Record debugging information for exception backtrace
  -no-g  Do not record debugging information (default)
  -function-sections  (option not available)
  -stop-after {parsing|typing|lambda|middle_end|linearization|emit|simplify_cfg|selection|register_allocation|llvmize} Stop after the given compilation pass.
  -save-ir-after {linearization|simplify_cfg|selection|llvmize} Save intermediate representation after the given compilation pass (may be specified more than once).
  -save-ir-before {register_allocation} Save intermediate representation before the given compilation pass (may be specified more than once).
  -probes  (option not available)
  -no-probes  Ignore [%%probe ..]
  -probes-optimized  (option not available)
  -no-probes-optimized  Emit naive code for [%%probe ..]
  -i  Print inferred interface
  -I <dir>  Add <dir> to the list of include directories
  -Ix <dir>  Add <dir> to the list of include directories
     (Like -I, but indicates that cmx files for modules in <dir> are
     always available)
  -H <dir>  Add <dir> to the list of "hidden" include directories
     (Like -I, but the program can not directly reference these dependencies)
  -I-manifest <file>  Get paths that the compiler can
    reference from a given manifest file. This option is an alternative
    to the -I flag, but specifies available files directly instead of
    adding whole directories to the search path. Each line of the
    manifest file should be in the format
    'file|manifest <visible_path> <actual_path>', where 'file' means
    that the line describes a file that the compiler can reference,
    'manifest' means that the compiler should read the specified
    manifest file recursively, <visible_path> is the path as interpreted
    by the compiler, <actual_path> is where this file is in the
    filesystem (relative to [$MANIFEST_FILES_ROOT]). The manifest file
    passed to the [-I-manifest] flag should itself be relative to
    [$MANIFEST_FILES_ROOT].
  -H-manifest <file>  Same as -I-manifest, but adds given
    paths to the list of "hidden" files (see -H for more details)
  -impl <file>  Compile <file> as a .ml file
  -inline <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  Aggressiveness of inlining (default 1.25, higher numbers mean more aggressive)
  -inline-toplevel <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  Aggressiveness of inlining at toplevel (higher numbers mean more aggressive)
  -inline-alloc-cost <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  The cost of not removing an allocation during inlining (default 7, higher numbers more costly)
  -inline-branch-cost <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  The cost of not removing a conditional during inlining (default 5, higher numbers more costly)
  -inline-call-cost <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  The cost of not removing a call during inlining (default 5, higher numbers more costly)
  -inline-prim-cost <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  The cost of not removing a primitive during inlining (default 3, higher numbers more costly)
  -inline-indirect-cost <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  The cost of not removing an indirect call during inlining (default 4, higher numbers more costly)
  -inline-lifting-benefit <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  The benefit of lifting definitions to toplevel during inlining (default 1300, higher numbers more beneficial)
  -inlining-report  Emit `.<round>.inlining' file(s) (one per round) showing the inliner's decisions (Flambda 1 and 2)
  -insn-sched  Run the instruction scheduling pass (default)
  -instantiate   Instantiates the first .cmx file, with the remaining ones used as the
  arguments for its parameters.
  -intf <file>  Compile <file> as a .mli file
  -intf-suffix <string>  Suffix for interface files (default: .mli)
  -keep-docs  Keep documentation strings in .cmi files
  -no-keep-docs  Do not keep documentation strings in .cmi files (default)
  -keep-locs  Keep locations in .cmi files (default)
  -no-keep-locs  Do not keep locations in .cmi files
  -labels  Use commuting label mode
  -linkall  Link all modules, even unused ones
  -requires-metaprogramming  Mark this unit as requiring metaprogramming support libraries
  -uses-metaprogramming  Link metaprogramming support libraries
  -llvm-backend  Enable LLVM backend (experimental)
  -inline-max-depth <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  Maximum depth of search for inlining opportunities inside inlined functions (default 1)
  -alias-deps  Do record dependencies for module aliases
  -no-alias-deps  Do not record dependencies for module aliases
  -linscan  Use the linear scan register allocator
  -app-funct  Activate applicative functors
  -no-app-funct  Deactivate applicative functors
  -directory  Directory to use for debug reporting like source code location reporting
  -no-float-const-prop  Deactivate constant propagation for floating-point operations
  -noassert  Do not compile assertion checks
  -noautolink  Do not automatically link C libraries specified in .cmxa files
  -nodynlink  Enable optimizations for code that will not be dynlinked
  -no-insn-sched  Do not run the instruction scheduling pass
  -nolabels  Ignore non-optional labels in types
  -nostdlib  Do not add default directory to the list of include directories
  -no-auto-include-otherlibs Add only stdlib to the list of include directories (unless -nostdlib is specified). Do not add subdirectories of other libraries distributed with the compiler (such as unix, str, dynlink). Do not alert when they are missing.
  -nocwd  Do not implicitly add the current directory to the load path
  -nopervasives  (undocumented)
  -no-unbox-free-vars-of-closures  Do not unbox variables that will appear inside function closures
  -no-unbox-specialised-args  Do not unbox arguments to which functions have been specialised
  -o <file>  Set output file name to <file>
  -O2  Apply increased optimization for speed
  -O3  Apply aggressive optimization for speed (may significantly increase code size and compilation time)
  -O4  Like -O3, but also enable the reaper pass (Flambda 2 only)
  -opaque  Does not generate cross-module optimization information
     (reduces necessary recompilation on module change)
  -open <module>  Opens the module <module> before typing
  -output-obj  Output an object file instead of an executable
  -output-complete-obj  Output an object file, including runtime, instead of an executable
  -p  (no longer supported)
  -pack  Package the given .cmx files into one .cmx
  -parameter <module name> Compile the module with <module name> as a parameter.
  -plugin <plugin>  (no longer supported)
  -pp <command>  Pipe sources through preprocessor <command>
  -ppx <command>  Pipe abstract syntax trees through preprocessor <command>
  -principal  Check principality of type inference
  -no-principal  Do not check principality of type inference (default)
  -rectypes  Allow arbitrary recursive types
  -no-rectypes  Do not allow arbitrary recursive types (default)
  -remove-unused-arguments  Remove unused function arguments
  -rounds <n>  Repeat tree optimization and inlining phases this many times (default 1).  Rounds are numbered starting from zero.
  -runtime-variant <str>  Use the <str> variant of the run-time system
  -ocamlrunparam <settings>  Use the given OCAMLRUNPARAM settings as the default (ignored except when linking an executable)
  -with-runtime Include the runtime system in the generated program (default)
  -without-runtime Do not include the runtime system in the generated program.
  -S  Keep intermediate assembly file
  -safe-string  (default unconditionally since 5.0)
  -safer-matching  Do not use type information to optimize pattern-matching
  -shared  Produce a dynlinkable plugin
  -short-paths  Shorten paths in types
  -strict-sequence  Left-hand part of a sequence must have type unit
  -no-strict-sequence  Left-hand part of a sequence need not have type unit (default)
  -strict-formats  Reject invalid formats accepted by legacy implementations (default)
     (Warning: Invalid formats may behave differently from
      previous OCaml versions, and will become always-rejected
      in future OCaml versions. You should always use this flag
      to detect invalid formats so you can fix them.)
  -no-strict-formats  Accept invalid formats accepted by legacy implementations
     (Warning: Invalid formats may behave differently from
      previous OCaml versions, and will become always-rejected
      in future OCaml versions. You should never use this flag
      and instead fix invalid formats.)
  -thread  (deprecated) same as -I +threads
  -unbox-closures  Pass free variables via specialised arguments rather than closures
  -unbox-closures-factor <n > 0>  Scale the size threshold above which unbox-closures will slow down indirect calls rather than duplicating a function (default 10)
  -inline-max-unroll <n>|<round>=<n>[,...]  Unroll recursive functions at most this many times (default 0)
  -unboxed-types  unannotated unboxable types will be unboxed
  -no-unboxed-types  unannotated unboxable types will not be unboxed (default)
  -ddebug-uids  dump debug uids when printing variables
  -ddebug-uid-tables  dump tables associating debug uids with shapes
  -unsafe  Do not compile bounds checking on array and string access
  -v  Print compiler version and location of standard library and exit
  -verbose  Print calls to external commands
  -verbose-types  Print detailed information within types
  -no-verbose-types  Omit expert information within types (default)
  -kind-verbosity <n>  Set the verbosity used for printing kinds (0=not verbose, 1=expanded, 2=expanded with all mod bounds)
  -version  Print version and exit
  --version  Print version and exit
  -vnum  Print version number and exit
  -w <list>  Enable or disable warnings according to <list>:
        +<spec>   enable warnings in <spec>
        -<spec>   disable warnings in <spec>
        @<spec>   enable warnings in <spec> and treat them as errors
     <spec> can be:
        <num>             a single warning number
        <num1>..<num2>    a range of consecutive warning numbers
        <letter>          a predefined set
     default setting is "+a-4-7-9-27-29-30-32..42-44-45-48-50-60-66..70-183..184"
  -warn-error <list>  Enable or disable error status for warnings according
     to <list>.  See option -w for the syntax of <list>.
     Default setting is "-a"
  -warn-help  Show description of warning numbers
  -where  Print location of standard library and exit
  - <file>  Treat <file> as a file name (even if it starts with `-')
  -match-context-rows <n>  (advanced, see manual section 13.2.)
  -dno-unique-ids  (undocumented)
  -dunique-ids  (undocumented)
  -dno-locations  (undocumented)
  -dlocations  (undocumented)
  -dsource  (undocumented)
  -dparsetree  (undocumented)
  -dtypedtree  (undocumented)
  -dshape  (undocumented)
  -dtlambda  (undocumented)
  -dslambda  (undocumented)
  -drawlambda  (undocumented)
  -dlambda  (undocumented)
  -dblambda  Dump Blambda terms before bytecode generation
  -dletreclambda  Dump Lambda terms going into Value_rec_compiler
  -drawclambda  (undocumented)
  -dclambda  (undocumented)
  -dcmm-invariants  Extra sanity checks on Cmm
  -dflambda  Print Flambda (1 or 2) terms on exit from Flambda
  -drawflambda  Print Flambda terms after closure conversion
     (for Flambda 2, after [Lambda_to_flambda])
  -dflambda-invariants  Check Flambda (1 and 2) invariants
  -dflambda-heavy-invariants  Check Flambda 2 heavy invariants
  -dflambda-no-invariants  Do not check Flambda (1 and 2) invariants
  -dflambda-let <stamp>  Print when the given Flambda 1 [Let] is created
  -dflambda-verbose  Print Flambda 1 terms including around each pass
  -dcmm  (undocumented)
  -dcse  (undocumented)
  -dlinear  (undocumented)
  -dstartup  (undocumented)
  -dtimings  Print timings information for each pass
  -dtimings-precision <n>  Specify precision for timings information (default 3)
  -dcounters  Print counter information for each pass
  -dprofile  Print performance information for each pass
    The columns are: time alloc top-heap absolute-top-heap counters.
  -dgranularity {file|func|block} Specify granularity level for profile information (-dtimings, -dcounters, -dprofile)
  -dprofile-output <file>  Set output filename for profile data (e.g., array-profile.csv)
  -dump-into-file  dump output like -dlambda into <target>.dump
  -dump-into-csv  Dump profile information to profile.csv
  -dump-dir redirects any file(s) that would be outputted as a result of other flags
    to selected directory (adding stamp to ensure uniqueness in directory)
  -dump-pass  Record transformations performed by these passes: 
  -debug-ocaml  Debugging output for the compiler
(internal use only)
  -shape-format {old-merlin|debugging-shapes}  Set shape format (old-merlin|debugging-shapes) used in the compiler and stored in .cms files. Default is old-merlin unless configured with --enable-oxcaml-dwarf.
  -gdwarf-config-shape-reduce-depth <n|none>  Maximum depth for shape reduction in DWARF debug info (default: 2, use 'none' for unlimited)
  -gdwarf-config-shape-eval-depth <n|none>  Maximum depth for shape evaluation in DWARF debug info (default: 2, use 'none' for unlimited)
  -gdwarf-config-max-cms-files-per-unit <n|none>  Maximum CMS files per compilation unit in DWARF debug info (default: 20, use 'none' for unlimited)
  -gdwarf-config-max-cms-files-per-variable <n|none>  Maximum CMS files per variable in DWARF debug info (default: 5, use 'none' for unlimited)
  -gdwarf-config-max-type-to-shape-depth <n|none>  Maximum type-to-shape depth for generating DWARF debug info (default: 10, use 'none' for unlimited)
  -gdwarf-config-max-shape-reduce-steps-per-variable <n|none>  Maximum shape reduction steps per variable in DWARF debug info (default: 1000, use 'none' for unlimited)
  -gdwarf-config-max-evaluation-steps-per-variable <n|none>  Maximum evaluation steps per variable in DWARF debug info (default: 1000000, use 'none' for unlimited)
  -gdwarf-config-shape-reduce-fuel <n|none>  Fuel for shape reduction when producing DWARF debug info (default: 10, use 'none' for unlimited)
  -gdwarf-fidelity <level>  Set fidelity level of the DWARF debug information (low|medium|high|very-high|ultra-high|unlimited). Higher values produce more detailed debug information at the expense of increased compilation times.
	- low is fast, but it does not support recursive types or retrieving declaration information from other files
	- medium is a reasonable default (it does support recursive declarations), but it is conservative with respect to retrieving declarations (including finding them through functor application)
	- high and above should provide good debugging information at increased compilation times
  -args <file> Read additional newline-terminated command line arguments
      from <file>
  -args0 <file> Read additional null character terminated command line arguments
from <file>
  -depend <options> Compute dependencies (use 'ocamlopt -depend -help' for details)
  -help  Display this list of options
  --help  Display this list of options
